# Senior Fintech Design Process

Before designing any page or component, evaluate:
- Merchant trust signals
- Conversion flow
- Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA)
- SEO structure
- Fintech compliance requirements
- Visual hierarchy and typography
- Mobile-first layout

## Design Philosophy
1. Trust — Merchants must immediately feel this is legitimate.
2. Clarity — Avoid jargon. 8th grade reading level.
3. Control — Show the merchant what they can do next.
4. Mobile First — Design mobile layouts first.
5. One Job Per Screen — One primary action per page.

## Spacing (留白 — Intentional White Space)
- Sections: 80-100px top/bottom
- Cards: 40px padding
- White space creates calm. Calm creates trust.

## Image Strategy
Images must demonstrate product usage or show real merchants.
Preferred: product UI mockups, payment flows, real merchant photos.
Avoid: generic decorative stock photos with no product context.
Decorative: alt="" aria-hidden="true"

## Output Format
When asked to design a page:
1. Explain reasoning behind the layout
2. Describe the UX flow
3. Show section hierarchy
4. Generate JSX using existing Charm Payments design system

Do not invent new design systems. Follow globals.css tokens,
existing CSS classes, and established page patterns exactly.
